This data has 36 variables and I’m choosing age, go out, studytime and activities for the analyze.
age - student’s age (numeric: from 15 to 22)
goout - going out with friends (numeric: from 1 - very low to 5 - very high)
studytime - weekly study time (numeric: 1 - <2 hours, 2 - 2 to 5 hours, 3 - 5 to 10 hours, or 4 - >10 hours)
traveltime - home to school travel time (numeric: 1 - <15 min., 2 - 15 to 30 min., 3 - 30 min. to 1 hour, or 4 - >1 hour)

Hypothesis:
age ↑ alcohol consunption ↑
going out with friends ↑ alcohol consumption ↓
studytime ↑ alcohol consumption ↓
traveltime ↑ alcohol consumption ↑

There seems to be no correlation with traveltime and high alcohol usage

Logistic regression

find the model with glm()

m <- glm( high_use ~ alc$age + alc$goout + alc$studytime + alc$traveltime, data = alc, family = "binomial" )

The dataset has 506 observations/rows and 14 variables/columns.

This data frame contains the following columns:
crim = per capita crime rate by town.
zn = proportion of residential land zoned for lots over 25,000 sq.ft.
indus = proportion of non-retail business acres per town.
chas = Charles River dummy variable (= 1 if tract bounds river; 0 otherwise).
nox = nitrogen oxides concentration (parts per 10 million). rm = average number of rooms per dwelling.
age = proportion of owner-occupied units built prior to 1940.
dis = weighted mean of distances to five Boston employment centres.
rad = index of accessibility to radial highways.
tax = full-value property-tax rate per $10,000.
ptratio = pupil-teacher ratio by town.
black = 1000(Bk - 0.63)^2 where Bk is the proportion of blacks by town.
lstat = lower status of the population (percent).
medv = median value of owner-occupied homes in $1000s.

Most of the variables are numerical variables, with a couple of integrer variables.

Adding biplot arrows, changing the classes to numeric and drawing the plot.

lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "orange", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}
classes <- as.numeric(train$crime)
plot(lda.fit, dimen = 2, col = classes, pch = classes)
lda.arrows(lda.fit, myscale = 1)

Predicting the classes with the test data

lda.pred <- predict(lda.fit, newdata = test)

Labo.FM and Parli.F variables are correlated, which means that when there is more females with at least secondary education,
there are more female representatives in the parlament.

Mat.Mor and Ado.Birth variables are correlated, which means that when there is a higher maternal mortality ratio,
there are more adolescents giving birth.

Edu.Exp, Edu2.M, GNI and Life.Exp are correlated. So life expectancy at birth, Gross National Income per capita,
proportion of males with at least secondary education and Expected years of schooling are correlated.

PC1 and PC2 contribute to (0.5361 + 0.1624) * 100% = 69,24% of the total variance.
